I"‹	<p>Recently, I was going through some course on Internet when I came across PowerShell. We used to work with a program called cmd.exe, but always wanted to have the usability and power that Unix command line offers. If you are using Windows 7 or later, then you just need to follow following steps:-</p>

<ul>
  <li>Click Start.</li>
  <li>In ‚ÄúSearch programs and files‚Äù, type: <code class="highlighter-rouge">powershell</code> and press Enter.</li>
</ul>

<p>This will open a cmd.exe like window.</p>

<p>If you are still working on Windows XP, like me, then you can download the PowerShell from <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/download/en/details.aspx?displaylang=en&amp;id=16818">here</a>.</p>

<p>You can try the following commands on powershell:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>pwd</strong><br />
  print working directory</li>
  <li><strong>hostname</strong><br />
  computer‚Äôs network name</li>
  <li><strong>mkdir</strong> <br />
  make directory</li>
  <li><strong>cd</strong> <br />
  change directory</li>
  <li><strong>ls</strong> <br />
  list directory</li>
  <li><strong>rmdir</strong> <br />
  remove directory</li>
  <li><strong>pushd</strong> <br />
  push directory</li>
  <li><strong>popd</strong> <br />
  pop directory</li>
  <li><strong>cp</strong> <br />
  copy a file or directory</li>
  <li><strong>robocopy</strong> <br />
  robust copy</li>
  <li><strong>mv</strong> <br />
  move a file or directory</li>
  <li><strong>more</strong> <br />
  page through a file</li>
  <li><strong>type</strong> <br />
  print the whole file</li>
  <li><strong>forfiles</strong> <br />
  run a command on lots of files</li>
  <li><strong>dir -r</strong> <br />
  find files</li>
  <li><strong>select-string</strong> <br />
  find things inside files</li>
  <li><strong>help</strong> <br />
  read a manual page</li>
  <li><strong>helpctr</strong> <br />
  find what man page is appropriate</li>
  <li><strong>echo</strong> <br />
  print some arguments</li>
  <li><strong>set</strong> <br />
  export/set a new environment variable</li>
  <li><strong>exit</strong> <br />
  exit the shell</li>
  <li><strong>runas</strong> <br />
  DANGER! become super user root DANGER!</li>
  <li><strong>attrib</strong> <br />
  change permission modifiers</li>
  <li><strong>iCACLS</strong> <br />
  change ownership</li>
</ul>

<p>I am still trying to learn these commands. Will come up with details when I know about each of them. There are few that you already know. So, let us get started.</p>

<p>Enjoy Powershell!!</p>
